metadata.name: Collapsing System #11
metadata.description:
It started with a simple algorithm for the visualization of our Solar system. Nothing special, just Newton’s laws and gravitation. F = G x m1 x m2 / R^2, a = F / m.

Then it came to thoughts about the end. Planetary systems can live for billion years… until the moment when something breaks their balance. So I decided to model a situation when some stable planetary system encountered a little distortion. And it turns out really fascinating.

Now I want to share it with you - your own planetary system apocalypse. 

Press 1 to save png with 2400px resolution.
Press 2 to save png with 4800px resolution.
Press 3 to save png with 9600px resolution.

It makes take some time to render, please be patient.

metadata.name: Aquarelle #115
metadata.description:
Mimicking the art of watercolours.

Save as png:
Click “s”
or double click/tap

Resolution:
Default image width = 2000px and aspect ratio = 4:3.
Modify the image width between 2000px and 10000px by adding “&w=xxxx” to the url (e.g. &w=4000).
High resolutions are computationally expensive and may take a while.

Background:
The canvas background texture is visible by default. This can be toggled off by adding “&b=0” to the url.
The background scales with resolution to mimic a bigger canvas so it will look different at different resolutions.
At high resolutions a Moiré pattern may appear on the canvas background texture due to the way images are resized in the browser. It’s always recommended to download a full resolution version of the piece.

By KRANKARTA
Created on Firefox desktop 105.0 on 2022-11-11 in javascript and GLSL.
CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Averno #24
metadata.description:
The work sits at the intersection of atmospheric abstraction and symbolic representation,
where generative aesthetics become a vehicle for an exploration of the perceptual threshold between form and dissolution.
Vertical structures, resembling slender shrubs or nervous filaments, construct a visual lattice that oscillates between transparency and density, suggesting a synthetic vegetation suspended between nature and algorithm.

The composition stands out for its use of digital color, with gradients that simulate traditional techniques such as pastel or watercolor, while maintaining a coherence typical of code. The generative intervention is not merely ornamental: it is a formal strategy that translates the indeterminacy of the landscape into an autonomous aesthetic language.

The sinuous shapes that emerge from below and rise upwards are not mere presences: they suggest a humanity in the making—or rather, an anthropomorphic echo generated by the system, a tension between organic mark-making and computational logic.

metadata.name: MOYO #75
metadata.description:
MOYO is generative piece building unique patterns.
The first algorithm was created in 2018, while visiting Kanazawa, a city on the west side of Japan.
Originally inspired by some kimono embroidery, I created some set of rules that will give life, recursively, to patterns generated inside a squared area.

Thanks to fxhash, I can pursue the original generative vision of those patterns by evolving the algorithm, and here comes MOYO.
This collection of 1024 pieces waiting to be minted offers new compositions, new rules and new colors.
During the iterative crafting process, I've been surprised by the algorithm which offered some unexpected kind of results, which have been kept for the final generation.

Artist: Florian Zumbrunn
@florianzumbrunn

metadata.name: Minimal perturbation #9
metadata.description:
Repeating a small, subtle change until it becomes the only thing to be seen.
Even imperceptible changes can bring a (completely different) perspective.

Open live mode and press 'S' to download SVG.
Press 'P' to add frame and landmarks for plotting.

metadata.name: Antiflow #404
metadata.description:
"Opposites are not contradictory but complementary." - Niels Bohr

The concept of yin and yang is an ancient philosophy about how opposing forces are not only complementary but actually give rise to each other. This idea reverberates through nature, art, and life itself. Now it is at the heart of modern physics. Perhaps this is a fundamental law of nature baked into the very fabric of existence.

Antiflow is an exploration of how balanced complexity can arise from chaos by harnessing the dynamic interplay of opposing forces. To that end we were inspired to create this wildly unique set by mixing modern physics concepts with abstract expressionism and retro 3D primitives.

The aspect ratio is 3:2 to facilitate poster size prints and device wallpapers. Results are presented without borders, noise, or other effects to allow for maximum detail. Feel free to rotate in whatever direction you choose for the best display.

Press "S" to save at a higher definition.
tags: chaos opposites retro expressionist antiparticle flow p5js

metadata.name: SoulSea #131
metadata.description:
The Soul Sea

You look down and find that the ocean in your heart is a sine wave. 
The tide gently laps onto the shore.

The soul is the sea. You are the land. 
There are waves on the shore, and the waves are slices.

Gazing at the slices, you feel the coldness of the Arctic Ocean, the permafrost of the Antarctic Sea, the deep darkness of the bottomless sea.

Stay silent, hear the sound of the waves lapping at the innumerable shores far away.
Feel the soul of the digital ocean.

Interactivities:
> Key P: Pause
> Key S: Save
> Press and move mouseX: wave moves slower / faster

Che-Yu Wu
